	<p id = "message1" style = "word-wrap: break-word;">Earthquakes are defined as sudden and violent movements of the ground that can cause great destruction in the areas 
in which they occur. Given the intense power of these natural disasters, the first person who witnessed an earthquake must have certainly 
had a groundbreaking experience! All (bad) jokes aside, earthquakes are a serious problem that typically result from cracks along tectonic 
plate boundaries. So what makes earthquakes so destructive? When a tectonic plate boundary cracks (referred to as a "fault"), the sudden 
release of energy resulting from this fault spreads out in all directions, causing the ground to shake and move as the crack quickly 
expands. This can pose a huge threat to surrounding buildings, houses, and wildlife. And that's not all -- many earthquakes have 
less-than-pleasant side effects, including landslides, mudslides, and avalanches caused by the intense shaking of the ground, all of 
which can devastate an area and result in even more infrastructure collapse, deaths, and environmental damage post-earthquake. Given all 
of the harmful effects of these natural disasters, it would be extremely helpful to be able to predict when and where destructive 
earthquakes would be likely to occur. As of right now, the United States Geological Survey (USGS), nor any other scientists, have ever 
been able to predict a major earthquake.
<br>I wanted to take on the challenge of predicting the precise location, time, and magnitude of earthquakes. So, I began to research 
earthquakes and their possible triggers, and, through using historical data and observations of seismic activity, I have been able to 
create an advanced machine learning algorithm that accurately predicts the location, time and magnitude of earthquakes around the world. 
This is the core of <b>EarthquAIkes</b>, which aims to utilize artificial intelligence software and machine learning techniques to accurately 
predicts earthquakes. Please view the tab titled <i>Earthquake Prediction Map</i> to view an interactive map displaying all of this information 
in a visual format.</br>
</p>
